snippet.textDisplay:
Personally it was less about a photographer aesthetic when I was looking at the photos. I felt like when I was looking at it I was picking the ones with a less blurred background, because I was scanning the whole image for information, not just your focal point.

I'm not a photographer, nor do I really have any credibility of photography, but more pieces of an image that are visually accurate just kinda makes me feel like there's more to the photo.

The Note 10+ clearly had the focus of the image in frame, but you could also look to the ground and see the grooves on the ground.

snippet.textDisplay: I think the photo composition and main subject have a bigger influence than you may think. A good photographer would be able to spot the most interesting or beautiful thing in a particular scene, or even shot it in a way that make it so. Just because you make a thing the main subject of a photo doesn't mean people want to look at it. If the most interesting thing is in the background and the ”High quality” camera blurs it out, people can feel irritated. A good photo can be taken by a disposable camera, and a high end camera can take shit photos too.
